# GitHub workflow

## Branches

- **Always create a branch** for any feature, fix, or test task. Never commit directly to `main`.
- **Naming:** `<tool-or-harness>/<short-descriptor>` using kebab-case. **Tool or harness** is the primary system assisting with the branch (use a short, consistent lowercase slug): e.g. `cursor/…` (Cursor), `claude/…` (Claude Code), `codex/…`, or another you standardize for this repo. The **descriptor** must reflect the actual work, not the chat title (e.g. `cursor/bde-form-tests`, not `cursor/review-ad-campaign-abc123`). For work with no agent assist, `manual/…` is fine.

## Pull requests

- **Always open a PR** when a feature, fix, or test task is complete. Create it via GitHub MCP tools.
- **Never merge the PR.** Katy reviews CI checks and the Vercel preview before merging.
- **One PR per logical unit of work.** Don't bundle unrelated changes.
- **Never have two PRs open for the same work item.** If a PR exists for the current task, push additional fixes to that branch rather than opening a new PR. Keep iterating on the existing PR until all checks pass.
- **PR description** must include: what changed, why, and a test plan (how to verify it works).

### Single draft PR until merge (default)

- Prefer **one active branch + one PR** per ongoing effort. Keep **adding commits to that branch** and **updating the same PR** until Katy approves and merges. Avoid opening many parallel branches/PRs for follow-ups in the same workstream.
- Open the PR as a **draft** while iterating; mark **ready for review** when Katy should look.
- Start a **new** branch + PR only after the previous one is merged, or when the work is **clearly unrelated** (different experiment, different product surface).
- If using GitHub CLI: `gh pr create --draft` for new PRs; push additional commits to the same branch to refresh the existing PR.

## Commits

See `commit-messages.mdc` for commit message format (conventional commits, imperative mood, 50-char subject).
